diagnoses.name: Viral Infection
diagnoses.reasoning: Many viral infections can cause lymphadenopathy, leukopenia, and otitis media. Eye irritation and restless legs might not be direct symptoms but could be related to the general immune response or specific viruses.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Disorders
diagnoses.reasoning: Certain autoimmune conditions like lupus or Sjögren's syndrome can cause eye irritation, lymphadenopathy, and can lead to leukopenia due to immune dysregulation.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.reasoning: HIV/AIDS can lead to lymphadenopathy, leukopenia due to the virus's attack on the immune system. Eye irritation and otitis media can occur due to opportunistic infections.

diagnoses.name: Measles
diagnoses.reasoning: Measles can cause otitis media, eye irritation (conjunctivitis), and lymphadenopathy. Leukopenia and general discomfort could also manifest, including symptoms like restless legs due to fever or malaise.

diagnoses.name: Mononucleosis
diagnoses.reasoning: Caused by the Epstein-Barr virus, it can lead to lymphadenopathy, leukopenia, and eye irritation. Symptoms like fatigue can be associated with restless legs.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.reasoning: While primarily affecting joints, it can also cause lymphadenopathy, leukopenia, and eye irritation as secondary symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.reasoning: Transmitted by ticks, it can cause lymphadenopathy, leukopenia, and eye irritation. Restless legs might be related to neurological manifestations of the disease.

diagnoses.name: Allergic Reactions
diagnoses.reasoning: Can cause eye irritation directly and possibly lymphadenopathy. Some severe allergic reactions may lead to a drop in white blood cell count (leukopenia) and otitis media in rare situations.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.reasoning: A condition leading to granulomas in lymph nodes and other tissues could cause lymphadenopathy and eye irritation. Leukopenia could occur due to bone marrow involvement.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis
diagnoses.reasoning: TB can cause lymphadenopathy and leukopenia. Eye irritation might occur due to associated uveitis, and restless legs could be a symptom related to systemic infection.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A condition where poor blood flow to the brain results in cell death, causing symptoms such as weakness, headache, and aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a minibar, a temporary blockage of blood flow to the brain, potentially causing temporary weakness, headache, and difficulty with speech.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: An abnormal growth of cells within the brain that can cause pressure effects leading to headache, weakness on one side of the body, and aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the membranes covering the brain and spinal cord, known for causing headaches, fever, and in severe cases, symptoms similar to stroke.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic illness involving your central nervous system (CNS) where the immune system attacks the myelin, causing symptoms like weakness, speech disturbances, and headaches.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A severe headache often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and sensitivity to light. In some cases, speech disturbances may occur.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: A central nervous system disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing periods of unusual behavior, sensations, and sometimes loss of awareness.

diagnoses.name: Brain Abscess
diagnoses.description: A collection of pus that develops in the brain due to an infection, causing headache, fever, aphasia, and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Encephalitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the brain often caused by a virus, resulting in fever, headache, confusion, seizures, and in severe cases, weakness and speech problems.

diagnoses.name: Hemorrhagic Stroke
diagnoses.description: Occurs when a weakened blood vessel ruptures and bleeds into the surrounding brain, leading to symptoms such as sudden headache, weakness, and difficulty with speech or aphasia.

diagnoses: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE) with CNS involvement

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A condition where poor blood flow to the brain results in cell death, causing symptoms like weakness and aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Brain tumor
diagnoses.description: An abnormal growth of cells within the brain, which can cause symptoms such as vomiting, weakness, and aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A severe headache often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and sensitivity to light. In some cases, may cause aura or speech disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Encephalitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the brain, often due to infection, causing symptoms such as fever, weakness, vomiting, and problems with speech.

diagnoses.name: Intracerebral hemorrhage
diagnoses.description: Bleeding within the brain tissue, causing sudden headache, vomiting, weakness, and possibly difficulty with speech.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the membranes covering the brain and spinal cord, characterized by fever, vomiting, weakness, and in severe cases, confusion or aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Transient ischemic attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a TIA produces similar symptoms to a stroke, like speech disturbance and weakness, but usually lasts only a few minutes.

diagnoses.name: Multiple sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease of the central nervous system impairing the brain and spinal cord, which may cause symptoms such as weakness, problems with coordination, and in some cases, speech difficulties.

diagnoses.name: Epileptic seizure
diagnoses.description: A disorder in which nerve cell activity in the brain is disturbed, causing seizures. During or after seizures, individuals may experience weakness, confusion, and speech problems.

diagnoses.name: Brain abscess
diagnoses.description: A collection of pus that develops in the brain due to infection, causing increased intracranial pressure, vomiting, weakness, and can impair speech.
